The Gauteng government says its economy is expected to grow by 0.8% this year, above the national economy. JOHANNESBURG - The Gauteng government says its economy is expected to grow by 0.8% this year, above the national economy.Provincial Finance MEC Barbara Creecy delivered her medium term budget policy statement and the 2016/2017 adjustment budget at the provincial legislature earlier on Tuesday.Finance MEC Barbra Creecy is presenting medium term budget policy statement &amp; 2016/2017 adjustment budget at the provincial legislature.CM pic.twitter.com/BOkHcJkxytShe announced the provincial government will spend more than R250 billion over the next three years to ensure access to higher quality public education and better health care services.During his medium term budget policy statement last month finance Minister Pravin Gordhan revised the country's growth expectation to 0.5% from 0.9% this year, saying domestic constraints continue to limit the country s growth.Creecy says the provincial economy grew by 2.9% in the second quarter and is expected to grow by 0.8% this year.Gauteng prioritises health, education and infrastructure #GPMiniBudgethttps://t.co/HyubTd73EB#GPBudget gov says more than R250 billion will be spent to ensure access to higher quality public education &amp; better health care services.CM Key drivers of the recovery were manufacturing, finance and business services, agriculture and transport. She says in 2015, 209,000 jobs were created by the province and 47,000 net jobs in the first two quarters of this year, adding that the sectors that created employment are manufacturing, transport, finance and business services, trade and community services.(Edited by Zamangwane Shange)